<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-16 sm:py-24">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 lg:px-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400">Use cases / Postgres</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-50 md:text-5xl">
        Postgres ops — read-only triage, one-approval kill
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-8 text-zinc-400">
        At 02:14 a read replica falls 5 GB behind. A model with raw <code>psql</code>
        on the primary is either useful or terrifying — and you find out which one
        after it runs. With a declared Postgres pack, triage is read-only and
        unattended; anything that disconnects a backend stops for a human.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">The actions that matter here</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
        The
        <.link navigate={~p"/packs/postgres"} class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300">
          Postgres pack
        </.link>
        ships 48 actions. Five carry this incident; note where the risk tier sits.
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">postgres.replication_lag</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>, no args. One
          <code>SELECT … pg_wal_lsn_diff(…) FROM pg_stat_replication</code>
          on the primary; sent/replay lag in bytes per replica. The model polls it freely.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">postgres.longest_running_queries</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>. Active backends, oldest first,
          with PID, wait event, and the first 300 chars of the statement. No approval.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">postgres.lock_blocking_chains</code>
          — risk <code class="text-emerald-300">low</code>. Blocker → blocked PID pairs via <code>pg_blocking_pids()</code>. Find the head of the chain before you touch anything.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">postgres.cancel_query</code>
          — risk <code class="text-amber-300">high</code>. <code>pg_cancel_backend(pid)</code>:
          SIGINT, the connection survives. Argument is one integer PID (1–4194304). The default
          policy holds it for one approval.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code class="font-mono text-indigo-300">postgres.terminate_backend</code>
          — risk <code class="text-amber-300">high</code>. <code>pg_terminate_backend(pid)</code>:
          SIGTERM, the connection is severed and its transaction rolls back. The escalation when
          cancel won't take. Also one approval.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Worked example</h2>
      <pre class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-zinc-900 bg-black/60 p-4 font-mono text-xs leading-6 text-zinc-300"><span class="text-zinc-500"># LLM, via MCP. Every call carries a reason; it's logged.</span>

postgres.replication_lag &#123;&#125;
<span class="text-zinc-500">→ replica_1|10.0.0.6|streaming|async|0|2048
  replica_2|10.0.0.7|streaming|async|512|4812345678   # ~4.8 GB behind</span>

postgres.longest_running_queries &#123;&#125;
<span class="text-zinc-500">→ 9871|etl|analytics|1240|IO|DataFileRead|REINDEX TABLE orders_2018 ...
  4502|web|api|3|Lock|relation|UPDATE orders SET ...</span>

<span class="text-zinc-500"># Gentle first — cancel, don't kill. risk: high → one approval.</span>
postgres.cancel_query &#123;"pid": 9871,
  "reason": "20-min REINDEX on the primary starving WAL replay to replica_2."&#125;
<span class="text-zinc-500">→ status: pending_approval
  policy:  high tier → require_approval
  review:  https://app.emisar.dev/app/approvals/r_8f3a…</span></pre>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-zinc-400">
        The model hands the approval URL back to the human. The approver sees the actor, the
        target runner, the exact PID, and the reason — then approves with one click. The cancel
        fires, the output captures <code>pg_cancel_backend</code>'s boolean, and replay starts
        catching up. If the backend is wedged in a syscall and ignores the SIGINT, the model
        escalates to <code>postgres.terminate_backend</code> — which is its own approval, not a
        free upgrade.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-10 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">What stays out of bounds</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-zinc-300">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">No raw SQL.</strong>
          There is no <code>postgres.exec</code>
          and no <code>psql -c</code>
          passthrough. Every
          action runs one fixed statement with only validated, typed arguments substituted —
          a PID is an integer in <code>[1, 4194304]</code>, nothing else.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">No DDL.</strong>
          The pack's writes stop at cancel/terminate, <code>ANALYZE</code>, <code>VACUUM</code>,
          and <code>REINDEX CONCURRENTLY</code>
          — each individually risk-tiered. There is no <code>ALTER</code>
          or <code>DROP</code>
          to call.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">No raw secrets leave the host.</strong>
          <code>psql</code> connection errors and <code>PG*</code> environment values run through
          redaction on the runner before egress. The control plane never sees your database
          password.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-zinc-100">Shapes, not values.</strong>
          <code>postgres.slow_queries</code> reads <code>pg_stat_statements</code>, where literals
          are already normalized to <code>$1</code>. You get query fingerprints and timings —
          not the rows they touched.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <%!-- FAQ --%>
      <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl font-semibold text-zinc-50">Questions a Postgres on-call asks</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 divide-y divide-zinc-900 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-900 bg-zinc-950/60">
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            Can the model run an undeclared query?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            No. The runner only exposes the actions in the trusted pack, each a fixed SQL string.
            A statement that isn't one of those 48 doesn't exist as far as the model is concerned —
            there's no free-text SQL surface to reach.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            Why is killing a backend allowed at all?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Because clearing a blocker at 02:14 is the whole point. It's gated, not removed:
            <code>cancel_query</code>
            and <code>terminate_backend</code>
            ship at <code>high</code>,
            which the default policy holds for one human approval. Tighten it to <code>deny</code>
            for a given role, or grant a bounded standing approval — that's a
            policy decision, and the policy change is itself audited.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="group">
          <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-sm font-semibold text-zinc-100">
            Does the runner need superuser on the database?
            <.icon name="hero-plus" class="h-5 w-5 text-zinc-500 transition group-open:hidden" />
            <.icon name="hero-minus" class="hidden h-5 w-5 text-indigo-400 group-open:block" />
          </summary>
          <p class="px-6 pb-5 text-sm leading-6 text-zinc-400">
            Only the privileges the actions you enable require. The pack authenticates with libpq
            <code>PG*</code>
            env vars on the host; scope that role to <code>pg_monitor</code>
            plus <code>pg_signal_backend</code>
            if read-only triage and backend cancellation is all you
            expose.
          </p>
        </details>
      </div>

